---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Navigation from '../components/Navigation.astro';
import Breadcrumb from '../components/Breadcrumb.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

const title = "Recording Bird Speech";
const description = "Methods and techniques for recording and analyzing bird speech.";
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Navigation slot="navigation" currentPage="recording" />
  
  <article>
    <Breadcrumb currentPage="Recording Bird Speech" />

    <header class="page-header">
      <h1>Recording Bird Speech</h1>
    </header>

    <section class="content">
      <p>
        Recording bird speech for research purposes requires specialized techniques and 
        equipment. Unlike controlled laboratory settings, capturing natural speech from 
        a companion parrot involves patience and preparation.
      </p>

      <h2>Equipment Considerations</h2>
      <p>
        High-quality audio recording equipment is essential for capturing the nuances of 
        bird speech. Digital recorders with good frequency response can capture the full 
        range of a macaw's vocalizations, from low rumbles to high-pitched calls.
      </p>

      <h2>Recording Environment</h2>
      <p>
        The recording environment significantly affects audio quality. Background noise, 
        room acoustics, and microphone placement all play important roles. A quiet setting 
        with minimal echo produces the clearest recordings.
      </p>

      <h2>Natural vs. Prompted Speech</h2>
      <p>
        For research purposes, natural, unprompted speech provides the most valuable data. 
        When a bird speaks spontaneously without cues, we gain insight into genuine 
        language use rather than trained responses.
      </p>

      <h2>Documentation</h2>
      <p>
        Proper documentation accompanies each recording:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Date and time of recording</li>
        <li>Environmental conditions</li>
        <li>Context before and after the utterance</li>
        <li>The bird's apparent emotional state</li>
        <li>Any relevant preceding events</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Analysis Methods</h2>
      <p>
        Recorded speech can be analyzed using various methods, including:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Spectrographic analysis for acoustic properties</li>
        <li>Phonetic transcription for linguistic content</li>
        <li>Contextual analysis for meaning and intent</li>
        <li>Comparative analysis with human speech patterns</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Preservation</h2>
      <p>
        Audio recordings are preserved in multiple formats and locations to ensure 
        long-term availability for research and reference purposes.
      </p>
    </section>

    <Footer />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-header h1 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    color: #663300;
    text-align: center;
    margin-bottom: 40px;
  }

  .content {
    max-width: 750px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .content h2 {
    color: #009966;
    margin-top: 40px;
    margin-bottom: 15px;
    font-size: 1.4rem;
  }

  .content p {
    margin-bottom: 1.5em;
    color: #333;
  }

  .content ul {
    margin: 20px 0;
    padding-left: 30px;
  }

  .content li {
    margin-bottom: 10px;
    color: #444;
  }
</style>
